00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:45,000
 So this first one, look at how tilted back that back crotch is, and how long it is compared to the front.

191
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:51,000
 And look at these ladies riding trousers from the Keystone system for ladies garments in 1891.

192
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:55,000
 Look at that back crotch, look at the length and the tilt.

193
00:17:55,000 --> 00:18:01,000
 Given that this book comes with instructions for drafting that, I think I'll have to try and draft that sometime.

194
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:10,000
 And finally, look at the difference at the front crotch length and the back crotch length for these ladies riding trousers in 1892.

195
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:15,000
 I think riding trousers really need to be comfortable, so a nice long back crotch length will help with that.

196
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:22,000
 So onto the things that I've neglected to mention when I was drafting my block in video 2.

197
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:36,000
 So as I mentioned at the very beginning of this video, in video 2, at 4 minutes, 30 seconds of video 2, I covered plotting the point C to I, and I said use your low hip measurement plus 1 inch divided by 4.

198
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:44,000
 But the exception was, and there was only one exception, if your largest circumference is actually around your crotch thigh area.

199
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:56,000
 So if you do actually have really big thighs, or you have a drop bottom, or for whatever reason, your largest measurement is around your crotch thigh, then use that larger measurement.

200
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:03,000
 So I neglected to tell you that I had done that when I started drafting my front.

201
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:09,000
 And just a note here, C to I is the width of the foundation.

202
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:18,000
 Now just in case someone remembers me saying something along the lines of it not being a good idea to use the widest part of your body for the width of your foundation.

203
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:21,000
 When I said that, it was a completely different context.

204
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:27,000
 That was referring to block making instructions that basically used the hip to determine what the thigh is.

205
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:36,000
 In that context, if I used my largest circumference to draft the block, I'd end up with an additional 2 inches of ease in the thigh.

206
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:42,000
 So yes, that's a completely different thing. So we'll go back to what I was saying for my block in my system.

207
00:19:42,000 --> 00:19:46,000
 Pants are usually drafted to fit the hip, which is 2 inches above the crotch.

208
00:19:46,000 --> 00:19:54,000
 So when ready to wear clothing, if it fits my hip, and I'm larger down in the crotch, then obviously it pulls around the crotch.

209
00:19:54,000 --> 00:20:05,000
 Now point I is where the pants starts to bifurcate, as in it reaches the middle of my body, starts to turn in around my leg and goes between my legs.

210
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:19,000
 So obviously then if I use the smaller measurement, my low hip measurement from C to I, then it will start to turn in too soon, and I will get that strain and pulling across my thigh.

211
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:29,000
 So therefore, I need to plot C to I to reflect what my actual body width is there at that point before the fabric turns and goes between my legs.

212
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:40,000
 So the orange outline is what I want, what will suit my body. The green shading is what I'd get if I used my lower hip up above for the width of my foundation.

213
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:51,000
 Which leads me on to the second thing I neglected to cover when I was drafting my block. Because I am smaller at the lower hip, I need to take that into account when I do my waist shaping.

214
00:20:51,000 --> 00:21:00,000
 Now when I showed you my waist shaping, I didn't actually show you me taking into account my low hip, the fact that I needed to take some ease out at that level.

215
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:05,000
 I did take away a bit here, but then I added a bit on the outside.

216
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:16,000
 So when I compare the measurement J to M, which is my crotch level width to the pink arrow, which is the width of my block at the low hip, then the difference is 3/8 of an inch.

217
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:29,000
 So I actually have removed 3/8 of an inch from my low hip. Given that my low hip is 1 1/2 inches smaller than my crotch level width, 1 1/2 inches divided by 4 is 3/8 of an inch.

218
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:34,000
 So I need to remove 3/8 of an inch from the front and 3/8 of an inch from the back.

219
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:44,000
 Now however, if you find it hard to get the right shape or curve when you're trying to remove ease here in the low hip, you don't have to distribute it evenly between the front and the back.

220
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:52,000
 You could take off more at the front, less at the back or more in the back and less in the front. That's one thing.

221
00:21:52,000 --> 00:22:04,000
 Then when I got to the back, I again neglected to tell you that D to I, for me, was my crotch level circumference plus 1 inch divided by 4, not my low hip measurement plus 1 inch divided by 4.

222
00:22:04,000 --> 00:22:15,000
 And so then, like the front, I'm neglected to show you the ease being taken out of the low hip. Having said that, this brings me to an extremely important point for those with really curvy figures.

223
00:22:15,000 --> 00:22:27,000
 The pink line you see is my low hip line, and it should be, according to what I just told you in the previous slide, 3/8 of an inch smaller than D to I. In fact, it's exactly the same.

224
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:42,000
 Therefore, I've apparently only taken out 3/4 of an inch from my low hip at the front instead of 1 1/2 inches that I'm supposed to need to take out because my low hip is 1 1/2 inches smaller than my crotch level circumference.

225
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:57,000
 Now I have a story to tell. When I first drafted the block and I drafted it 1 1/2 inches less than the crotch depth circumference, it would consistently seem to be too tight and the low hip, and I would measure myself in the low hip again and again and again.

226
00:22:57,000 --> 00:23:12,000
 I kept on coming up with it was 1 1/2 inches less than my crotch depth circumference, but then when I'd make the block, it always seemed to tight when I used that measurement, and I will show you now why that is.

227
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:17,000
 I think maybe you can see what the problem is.

228
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:26,000
 The pink line is the correct measurement, but when I apply that measurement to the green line, well then it's incorrect.

229
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:34,000
 Now let me just say that generally what you see on the flat 2D block isn't always the same as the 3D representation.

230
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:52,000
 So probably if I had have turned my block over and traced it out and I saw that, I would have thought I know when it's on the body that will be a curve, but for me it just didn't seem to do that as you can see by my 12 and the lines on my 12.

231
00:23:52,000 --> 00:24:12,000
 Now in this image, I've actually put the tape measure right around that original green line, and you can see there that the tape measure kind of sits away from the body, and what I want to say is when you've got a really curvy body, sometimes part of the problem is the tape measure wants to sit flat.

232
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:32,000
 So sometimes the tape measure will ride up at the back more than the front, so sometimes you're taking an incorrect measurement, but sometimes the problem is to that what you'll think you're measuring when you put it on the block, that's not what where it ends up.

233
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:49,000
 So here are the takeaways from that last point, one, you must draw all the lines from the block onto your 12, and two, measure yourself not only before making the 12, but with the 12 on and see whether the tape measure is following those lines on the 12, especially if you are curvy.

234
00:24:49,000 --> 00:25:15,000
 So just a final summary, bottoms and thighs, one, crotch length is determined by your thigh size, buttock protrusion and buttock drop, and if you measure the largest around your crotch area, this can be due to larger than normal upper thighs, buttocks that overhang the thigh, protruding front thigh, muscle or fat at the crotch level, above upper thigh as it pertains to drafting pants, or more than one of the above.

235
00:25:15,000 --> 00:25:22,000
 The next video will be drafting the block for Jane, hopefully that video will be up very soon.

236
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:51,000
 So that's the end of this video, this is Maria from Dress Pattern Making Channel.

237
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:59,000
 [BLANK_AUDIO]

